Date: Thu, 09 Jul 1998 08:31:39 -0500
From: Dr. Craig Carter <CNCARTER@TVMDL.TAMU.EDU>

In this posting on Newcastle the statement is made:
"Newcastle disease is not transferable to humans..."
This is not the case, however. Those individuals in close association with
infected birds can have conjunctivitis, lung congestion, epiphora, chills,
fever, and pharyngitis. Transmission is by aerosol or the fecal-to-oral
route. The incubation period is short, 1-2 days.
Because of the necessity of close association with birds, this can be an
occupational illness of poultrymen, abattoir workers, game bird raisers
and veterinarians.
The Newcastle agent stands out in my mind because of my first course in
veterinary microbiology where we were warned about the zoonotic potential
of the organism!
