From: Terry Thomas <Terry.Thomas@nre.vic.gov.au>

Two issues arising from the Fresno Bee article of 30 June -
Occasional human
infections occur with conjunctivitis, laryngitis, pharyngitis and
tracheitis. Infections may become quite severe and lead to some lasting
impairment of vision. Person to person transmission of ND virus was
suspected during the 1971-72 Californian outbreak.
ND
virus remains infectious in bone marrow and muscles of slaughtered chickens
for at least 6 months at minus 20 degrees Celsius and for up to 4 months
at refrigerator temperatures. The importation of the virus to various
countries in frozen chickens has occurred.
See Fenner et al (1987), Veterinary Virology, Academic Press See also
AUSVETPLAN (The Australian Veterinary Emergency Plan) Newcastle Disease
strategy at
<http://www.brs.gov.au/brs/aphb/aha>
--
Terry Thomas
Principal Veterinary Officer
